eligious thought on seemingly secular institutions and uncovers a spiritual, collectivist streak in the discourse of humanity. Because the humanitarian model of care transcends the boundaries of the state, and its networks touch much of the globe, Humanitarian Fictions redraws the boundaries of literary classification based on a shared problem space rather than a shared national space. The book maps a transnational vein of Anglophone literature about Africa that features missionaries, humanitarians, and their so-called beneficiaries. Putting humanitarian thought in conversation with postcolonial critique, this book brings together African, British, and U.S. writers typically read within separate traditions. Paustian shows how the novel—with its profound sensitivity to narrative—can enrich the critique of white saviorism while also imagining alternatives that give African agency its due.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHumanitarianism in literature. 0aHumanitarianismzAfrica. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPostcolonial Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / African.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aAnglophone literature.  aaid.  ahuman rights.  ahumanitarian narrative.  ahumanitarianism.  anovel.  apostcolonial theory.  awhite savior narrative.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075168040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781531505509?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781531505509423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781531505509/original  a978-3-11-075168-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles